In the ongoing revision of the Anti-Corruption Commission (ACC) Bill noticed that the chapter on anti-corruption enforcement included the stipulation of a punishment known as ‘Securing the Integrity of the Justice System’.

This is a punishment that has been enforced for many years by some countries, namely the USA and UK. For example, during the Clinton impeachment trial in 1999, one of the conditions that Hillary Clinton was given in the plea agreement was to undergo five years of supervised release without mentioning whether it would include home confinement. There were speculations that the prison sentence was avoided so that Bill Clinton can easily leave the White House following his impeachment.

This article will focus on what ‘Securing the Integrity of the Justice System’ is, where it is enforced at the moment and whether this is an appropriate stipulation in the defence of corruption in Zambia.
